name: 4-chloro-3-nitrobenzaldehyde
Reason: The compound 4-chloro-3-nitrobenzaldehyde can be broken down into its functional groups for the purpose of understanding its melting point. The basic unit, benzene, has a typical melting point of 5.5°C. Each substituent will interact differently with the molecule and therefore contribute to altering the melting point. The aldehyde group (-C=O) generally increases melting point due to the possible hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions it introduces; this can be estimated as a +40 to +50°C addition. The nitro group (-NO2) is also known to significantly increase melting point because of its strong electron-withdrawing nature and capability of forming intermolecular hydrogen bonds; this can be an additional +50 to +60°C. However, the chlorine atom (Cl) is a heavier halogen which can have variable effects on the melting point. Chlorine can increase the melting point due to its polarizability and Van der Waals interactions, estimated as a +5 to +15°C addition. Adding these effects together gives us an estimated increase of +95 to +125°C from the benzene base.
